# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

Whenever you encounter such problems, just try breaking the string **into the smallest possible..**

Let me give you an example...

If i would have said you to find the **answer for string "ab"...**

Just **don't consider** "ab" as a whole, **consider "a"  as different** and the **other "b" as different** and then calculate the ans for both of them and then add them up....

This is how we are gonna approach our solution..

Let us say..you have the string as "abcdcba"

Now, we just need to break the string into two parts...

**1) First part is left one**

**2) Second part is right one..**

Now, let me explain me how you will break this string "abcdcba"

**Case 1 => "a"   + "bcdcba"  (It means "a" is on the left hand side and "bcdcba" is on the right side)**

**Case 2 => "ab" + "cdcba"**

**Case 3 => "abc" + "dcba"**

**Case 4 => "abcd" + "cba"**

**Case 5 => "abcdc" + "ba"**

**Case 6 => "abcdcb" + "a"**

Now, these are the 6 cases possible and we have to **return the min** of all these cases..

Case 1 will further break down into multiple cases and this will go on...like in case 1 the right part of the string was "bcdcba" and this will break into multiple cases...

But, what should be done after breaking....

Let us say, after **multiple times of breaking your case comes to be** 

**Case => "a" + "b"**

Now, if the string if of size 1, then how many times you will run the printer...The ans is 1

so in this case from the left side you get 1 and from right side you get 1, so ans becomes 2 and that is a valid answer ...

Now the question comes ..how do we write the code to break the string up..

```
        int ans = INT_MAX;

        for(int k= i; k<=j-1; k++)
        {
        ans = min(ans,solve(i,k,s,dp) + solve(k+1,j,s,dp));
        }
```

This is how you make all the cases...

Now..There will be a **special case**..you need to take care of

Let us say the case is something like this..

**Case => "a" + "a"**

Now, according to what i told you above..you will return 1 from left hand side and 1 from right hand side and will give an ans of 2...but but but...the ans is 1...so how do we tackel such a case...

SIMPLE...just make sure that **if s[i]==s[j]**, where i is the start pointer of the string and j is the end pointer... which means if both the chacters are same ..**you will return ans-1**...SIMPLE...


Now, what will be the **base case**...

if the **size of string is 1**, that means the end pointer and start pointer of the string is at same position then **just return 1**..because we need to run printer 1 time...

**Now, how do we memoize...**

Two paramaters are changing..

**1) index i(which is the start pointer of the string)**

**2) index j(which is the end pointer of the string)**

Now, just make a 2-d dp array and store the results in **dp[i][j]**...This is how you solve the question simply..


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
You are running a loop from 0 to n every time and every time you are breaking the strings in to two parts...(i,k) and (k+1,j)..and for both if them the for loop will run again in the next recursion step...so total **O(N * N * N)**
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

You made a 2-d dp array so **O(N * N)**

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    int solve(int i,int j,string &s,vector<vector<int>>&dp)
    {

        if(i==j)
        {
