```plaintext
1. Initialize dp array of size n x n with all values set to 0.
2. For i = n-1 to 0:
3.   Set dp[i][i] = 1 (Base case: single character requires one turn).
4.   For j = i+1 to n-1:
5.     Set dp[i][j] to a large value (e.g., INT_MAX) as a placeholder.
6.     For k = i to j-1:
7.       Compute minTurns = dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j].
8.       If s[i] == s[j], decrement minTurns by 1 (as we can print the entire remaining string with the same character).
9.       Update dp[i][j] to the minimum of its current value and minTurns.
10. Return dp[0][n-1].
```
```
class Solution
{
public:
    int strangePrinter(string s)
    {
        int n = s.length();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(n, 0));

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i)
        {
            dp[i][i] = 1; // base case : one character example : a -> 1
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; ++j)
            {
                dp[i][j] = INT_MAX; 
                for (int k = i; k < j; ++k) // k is the partition point
                {
                    int minTurns = dp[i][k] + dp[k + 1][j]; // dp[i][k] -> turns for s[i...k] and dp[k+1][j] -> turns for s[k+1...j]
                    if (s[i] == s[j])
                        minTurns--; // If s[i] and s[j] are the same, we need one less turn. || example : aabaa -> 2 turns instead of 3 
                    dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], minTurns); // minTurns is the minimum turns for s[i...j]
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0][n - 1]; // minimum turns for s[0...n-1]
    }
};


```

solutions.content:
Many posts alreay give the code and DP equations. Here are some explainations to understand the DP equations.

Two basic points:
1, When we print a string, we may have lots of optimal solutions. ***Printing the whole line with the first character at the first step can always yield one of the optimal solutions.*** My understanding is that, although we can print other characters first, we still need one step coming back to print the first character. So printing other characters first and coming back printing the first character with one extra step is equivavlent to print the first character in first step and then printing other characters. Since in the first step, printing one character is equivalent to printing whole line with that character, we can print the whole line with the first character in the first step. And this will always give us one optimal solution.

2, When we print s[i..j], characters from i to j in the line, if some character s[k] in the middle same as s[i], base on point 1, one optimal soltution is we print whole s[i..j] with s[i] first, this will print s[k] too. So the DP equation ***dp[i][j] = min(dp[i][j], dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j])*** holds, becase s[k] already printed when we print s[i] at the first step.

C++ Code:

	int strangePrinter(string s) {
        if (s.size() <= 1){return s.size();}

        /* 2-d dp, 
         * dp[i][j] = minimal steps need to print s[i..j]
         * dp[i][i] = 1;
         * dp[i][j] = min{1 + dp[i+1][j], dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j] for i < k <= j and s[i] = s[k]}
         */
        int memo[101][101], n = s.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i){
            memo[i][i] = 1; 
        }
        for (int l = 2; l <= n; ++l){
            for (int j = l - 1; j < n; ++j){
                int i = j - l + 1;

                memo[i][j] = (s[i] == s[j]) ? memo[i][j-1] : (1 + memo[i+1][j]);
                for (int k = i + 1; k < j; ++k){
                    if (s[i] == s[k]){
                        memo[i][j] = min(memo[i][j], memo[i][k-1] + memo[k+1][j]);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return memo[0][n-1];
    }

