# Intuition
The recursion is quite straightforward: 
0. For a string of a length n the answer is at most n. 
1. Trival cases are when length of the string is 0 or 1.
2. We need to check all possible ways to split a string on two and compare the result of the sum with the given one. The only exception is that if the end character matches the first one, we don't need to take into account the last one.

On top of this recursion we of course add a simple memorization: the state is a pair (start, end) representing the indexes in the substring. We use dictionary to cache the results.

Observe that we can replace any number of consequent occurences of the character by one character. So we do this to improve performance.

# Approach
