## Intuition
The problem requires finding the minimum number of turns the printer needed to print the given string with specific properties. We can use dynamic programming to efficiently solve this problem.

## Approach
1. Define a recursive function `f(i, j, s)` that returns the minimum number of turns needed to print the substring from index `i` to `j` in the string `s`.
2. Use memoization to store the results of overlapping subproblems in a 2D `dp` array.
3. If `i == j`, return 1 as it represents printing a single character.
4. If `s[i] == s[j]` or `s[j-1] == s[j]`, call the recursive function with the substring excluding the last character (`f(i, j-1, s)`).
5. If `s[i] == s[i+1]`, call the recursive function with the substring excluding the first character (`f(i+1, j, s)`).
6. Otherwise, find the minimum number of turns by considering the following cases:
   a. Printing all characters from `i` to `j-1` first and then the character at `j` (`f(i, j-1, s) + 1`).
   b. If there exists a character `s[k]` from `i+1` to `j-1` such that `s[k] == s[j]`, then calculate the minimum turns by printing the substrings `i` to `k-1` and `k` to `j-1` separately (`f(i, k-1, s) + f(k, j-1, s)`).
7. Update the `dp[i][j]` with the minimum number of turns calculated in step 6.
8. Return the final result `f(0, n-1, s)`.

## Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^3) where n is the length of the string `s`. The function `f(i, j, s)` takes O(n) time, and there can be at most O(n^2) unique subproblems.
- Space complexity: O(n^2) for the `dp` array used for memoization.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int n;
    vector<vector<int>> dp;
    int f(int i, int j, string& s){       
        if (dp[i][j]!=-1) return dp[i][j];
        if (i==j) return dp[i][j]=1;
        int ans;
        if (s[i]==s[j]||s[j-1]==s[j]) ans=f(i, j-1, s);
        else if (s[i]==s[i+1]) ans=f(i+1, j, s);
        else{
            ans=f(i,j-1, s)+1;
            for(int k=i+1; k<j; k++){
                if(s[k]==s[j])
                    ans=min(ans, f(i, k-1, s)+f(k, j-1, s));
            }
        }
        return dp[i][j]=ans;
    }
    int strangePrinter(string s) {
        n=s.size();
        dp.assign(n, vector<int>(n, -1));
        return f(0, n-1, s);
    }
};
```

