## Intuition

We are given a "strange printer" that can only print a sequence of the same character each time, and it can cover the original existing characters. The problem requires us to find the minimum number of turns the printer needs to print a given string `s`.

To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming. We will define a 2D array `dp`, where `dp[i][j]` represents the minimum number of turns needed to print the substring `s[i:j+1]`.

The base case for `dp[i][i]` is 1, as we can always print a single character in one turn.

We can then build the `dp` array by considering all possible substrings of `s` with lengths ranging from 2 to `n` (where `n` is the length of the input string `s`). For each substring `s[i:j+1]`, we can try all possible splits and calculate the minimum number of turns needed by considering different combinations of subproblems.

The transition function for `dp[i][j]` is as follows:
1. If `s[i] == s[j]`, we can reduce the problem to `dp[i][j-1]`, as we can cover the last character with the one we print at `s[j]`.
2. Otherwise, we need to try all possible splits and take the minimum turns needed for each split. We can do this by iterating over all possible `k` between `i` and `j-1`, inclusive, and calculating the number of turns needed for `dp[i][k]` and `dp[k+1][j]`.

Finally, the result will be stored in `dp[0][n-1]`, where `n` is the length of the input string `s`.

## Approach

1. Initialize a 2D array `dp` of size `n` \xD7 `n` to store the minimum number of turns needed for each substring.
2. Set the base case `dp[i][i] = 1` for all `i` from 0 to `n-1`.
3. Loop over the length of substrings (`len`) from 2 to `n`:
   - Loop over the starting index `i` from 0 to `n-len`.
   - Calculate the ending index `j = i + len - 1`.
   - If `s[i]` is equal to `s[j]`, set `dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-1]`.
   - Otherwise, initialize `dp[i][j]` to the maximum length (worst case).
   - Loop over the split index `k` from `i` to `j-1`:
     - Update `dp[i][j]` to the minimum value of `dp[i][j]` and `dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j]`.
4. The result will be stored in `dp[0][n-1]`.

## Complexity Analysis

The time complexity of this approach is O(n^3) due to the nested loops, where `n` is the length of the input string `s`. For each length `len`, we have `O(n)` possible substrings, and for each substring, we consider all possible splits, which also takes `O(n)` time. So the total time complexity is O(n^3).

The space complexity is O(n^2) to store the `dp` array.

## Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int strangePrinter(String s) {
        int n = s.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[n][n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            dp[i][i] = 1;
        }

        for (int len = 2; len <= n; len++) {
            for (int i = 0; i < n - len + 1; i++) {
                int j = i + len - 1;

                if (s.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i][j - 1];
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = len; // Initialize to worst case
                    for (int k = i; k < j; k++) {
                        dp[i][j] = Math.min(dp[i][j], dp[i][k] + dp[k + 1][j]);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[0][n - 1];
    }
}
```

The provided code implements the approach described above to find the minimum number of turns needed by the strange printer to print the given string `s`. The time complexity can be further optimized using memoization or other techniques.

